<paragraph id="8BC436C25E3CFF9C9EF0F9EAFBFF9EAD" blockId="5.[174,1037,1653,1675]" box="[174,1037,1653,1675]" pageId="5" pageNumber="106">
<heading id="D08C81AE5E3CFF9C9EF0F9EAFBFF9EAD" box="[174,1037,1653,1675]" fontSize="10" level="2" pageId="5" pageNumber="106" reason="5">
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3CFF9C9EF0F9EAFBFF9EAD" bold="true" box="[174,1037,1653,1675]" pageId="5" pageNumber="106">
Key to families of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D415E3CFF9C9F3CF9EAFE249EAC" box="[354,470,1653,1674]" class="Insecta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="106" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Neuroptera</taxonomicName>
occurring in 
<collectingCountry id="F36C76525E3CFF9C9C03F9EAFD5D9EAD" box="[605,687,1653,1675]" name="Ukraine" pageId="5" pageNumber="106">Ukraine</collectingCountry>
(modified from Aspök et al., 1980)
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36165495E3CFF9C9EF0F93DFB229F0D" pageId="5" pageNumber="106" type="key">
<key id="FFEA61F35E3CFF9F9EF0F93DFB3B9BE8" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="107" pageId="5" pageNumber="106">
<keyStep id="308F2E675E3CFF9C9EF0F93DFB229EF3" pageId="5" pageNumber="106">
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E3CFF9C9EF0F93DFB239E9E" blockId="5.[174,1233,1698,1835]" box="[174,1233,1698,1720]" pageId="5" pageNumber="106">
<keyLead id="308A95F75E3CFF9C9EF0F93DFB239E9E" box="[174,1233,1698,1720]" pageId="5" pageNumber="106">
1. Length of fore wing is more than 
<quantity id="4C839B275E3CFF9C9C64F93DFD999E9E" box="[570,619,1698,1720]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="106" unit="cm" value="3.0">3 cm</quantity>
. ........................................................................................................... 2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E3CFF9C9EF0F920FB229EF3" blockId="5.[174,1233,1698,1835]" box="[174,1232,1727,1749]" pageId="5" pageNumber="106">
<keyLead id="308A95F75E3CFF9C9EF0F920FB229EF3" box="[174,1232,1727,1749]" pageId="5" pageNumber="106">
— Length of fore wing less than 
<quantity id="4C839B275E3CFF9C9C4DF920FDB69EF3" box="[531,580,1727,1749]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="106" unit="cm" value="2.0">2 cm</quantity>
....................................................................................................................3
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="308F2E675E3CFF9F9EF0F943FB3B98D8" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="107" pageId="5" pageNumber="106">
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E3CFF9C9EF0F943FB229F0D" blockId="5.[174,1233,1698,1835]" pageId="5" pageNumber="106">
<keyLead id="308A95F75E3CFF9C9EF0F943FB229F0D" pageId="5" pageNumber="106">
2. Width of cubital sector more than 0.2 (c. 0.25) of fore wing width. Veins 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3CFF9C9D9DF943FC2A9ED7" box="[963,984,1756,1777]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="106">Sc</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3CFF9C9A57F943FBE59ED7" box="[1033,1047,1756,1777]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="106">R</emphasis>
fused into smooth curve towards the wing tip; distal cell between 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3CFF9C9C9CF966FD229F28" box="[706,720,1785,1806]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="106">R</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3CFF9C9D5FF966FCE59F28" box="[769,791,1785,1806]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="106">Rs</emphasis>
is elongated, being 4–7 times as long as wide (
<figureCitation id="13402A475E3CFF9C9EA1F88AFECC9F0D" box="[255,318,1813,1835]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[166,199,1704,1726]" captionTargetBox="[361,1040,1032,1662]" captionTargetId="figure-397@6.[342,1049,1004,1703]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 3. Fore wing venation: 3a — Myrmeleontidae (Distoleon Banks, 1810); 3b — Ascalaphidae (Libelloides Schaffer, 1763); 3c — Osmylidae (Osmylus Latreille, 1802); 3d — Chrysopidae (Chrysopa Leach, 1815); 3e — Sisyridae (Sisyra Burmeister, 1839); 3f — Mantispidae (Mantispа Illiger in Kugelann, 1798); 3g — Coniopterigidae (Conwentzia Enderlein 1905); 3h — Hemerobiidae (Hemerobius Linnaeus, 1758); R — radius, Rs — radial sector, Rt — radial triangular, dc — distal cell between R and Rs, Sc — subcostal vein; trz — tiny inserted veins. arranged between the terminal branches of longitudinal veins." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404186" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404186/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="106">FIg. 3a</figureCitation>
). Antenna gradually thickening towards the tip or clavate. ................................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D415E3CFF9C9A6FF88AFB229F0D" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[1073,1232,1813,1835]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="106" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Myrmeleontidae</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<subSubSection id="C36165495E3FFF9F9EF8FF30FB3B9BE8" pageId="6" pageNumber="107" type="multiple">
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E3FFF9F9EF8FF30FB3B98D8" blockId="6.[166,1225,175,974]" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
<keyLead id="308A95F75E3FFF9F9EF8FF30FB3B98D8" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
— Width of cubital sector less than 0.15 (usually 0.1) of fore wing width. The vein 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3FFF9F9DAEFF30FBD398E2" box="[1008,1057,175,196]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
Sc+ 
<collectionCode id="ED6AAE075E3FFF9F9A4CFF30FBD398E2" box="[1042,1057,175,196]" country="Chile" name="Departamento de Geologia, Universidad de Chile" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">R</collectionCode>
</emphasis>
right after fusing steeply bent backwards; distal cell (
<figureCitation id="13402A475E3FFF9F9C64FF53FD8598C4" box="[570,631,204,226]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[166,199,1704,1726]" captionTargetBox="[361,1040,1032,1662]" captionTargetId="figure-397@6.[342,1049,1004,1703]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 3. Fore wing venation: 3a — Myrmeleontidae (Distoleon Banks, 1810); 3b — Ascalaphidae (Libelloides Schaffer, 1763); 3c — Osmylidae (Osmylus Latreille, 1802); 3d — Chrysopidae (Chrysopa Leach, 1815); 3e — Sisyridae (Sisyra Burmeister, 1839); 3f — Mantispidae (Mantispа Illiger in Kugelann, 1798); 3g — Coniopterigidae (Conwentzia Enderlein 1905); 3h — Hemerobiidae (Hemerobius Linnaeus, 1758); R — radius, Rs — radial sector, Rt — radial triangular, dc — distal cell between R and Rs, Sc — subcostal vein; trz — tiny inserted veins. arranged between the terminal branches of longitudinal veins." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404186" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404186/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">FIg. 3b</figureCitation>
) between 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3FFF9F9C86FF53FD1498C7" box="[728,742,204,225]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
<collectionCode id="ED6AAE075E3FFF9F9C86FF53FD1498C7" box="[728,742,204,225]" country="Chile" name="Departamento de Geologia, Universidad de Chile" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">R</collectionCode>
</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3FFF9F9D4AFF53FCD898C7" box="[788,810,204,225]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">Rs</emphasis>
short, quadrangular or nearly square, being 1.5 times as long as wide. Antenna clavate, long. ........................................................................ 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D415E3FFF9F9A0CFF77FB3B98D8" box="[1106,1225,232,254]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Ascalaphidae</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<keyStep id="308F2E675E3FFF9F9EF8FE9AFB3B9954" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E3FFF9F9EF8FE9AFB3B991E" blockId="6.[166,1225,175,974]" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
<keyLead id="308A95F75E3FFF9F9EF8FE9AFB3B991E" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
3. Radial sector always includes three cells; 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3FFF9F9CDAFE99FD60993D" box="[644,658,262,283]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
<collectionCode id="ED6AAE075E3FFF9F9CDAFE99FD60993D" box="[644,658,262,283]" country="Chile" name="Departamento de Geologia, Universidad de Chile" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">R</collectionCode>
</emphasis>
vein forming 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3FFF9F9D7EFE99FCC7993D" box="[800,821,262,283]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">Rt</emphasis>
(radial triangular) in front of the FIrst 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3FFF9F9AECFE99FB3A993D" box="[1202,1224,262,283]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">Rs</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="13402A475E3FFF9F9EA6FEBDFEC6991E" box="[248,308,290,312]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[166,199,1704,1726]" captionTargetBox="[361,1040,1032,1662]" captionTargetId="figure-397@6.[342,1049,1004,1703]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 3. Fore wing venation: 3a — Myrmeleontidae (Distoleon Banks, 1810); 3b — Ascalaphidae (Libelloides Schaffer, 1763); 3c — Osmylidae (Osmylus Latreille, 1802); 3d — Chrysopidae (Chrysopa Leach, 1815); 3e — Sisyridae (Sisyra Burmeister, 1839); 3f — Mantispidae (Mantispа Illiger in Kugelann, 1798); 3g — Coniopterigidae (Conwentzia Enderlein 1905); 3h — Hemerobiidae (Hemerobius Linnaeus, 1758); R — radius, Rs — radial sector, Rt — radial triangular, dc — distal cell between R and Rs, Sc — subcostal vein; trz — tiny inserted veins. arranged between the terminal branches of longitudinal veins." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404186" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404186/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">FIg. 3f</figureCitation>
). Fore leg raptorial. .............................................................................................................. 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D415E3FFF9F9A0CFEBDFB3B991E" authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[1106,1225,290,312]" class="Insecta" family="Mantispidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Mantispidae</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E3FFF9F9EF8FEA0FB3B9954" blockId="6.[166,1225,175,974]" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
<keyLead id="308A95F75E3FFF9F9EF8FEA0FB3B9954" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
— Radial sector always includes more than three cells; 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3FFF9F9CB6FEDFFD049973" box="[744,758,320,341]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
<collectionCode id="ED6AAE075E3FFF9F9CB6FEDFFD049973" box="[744,758,320,341]" country="Chile" name="Departamento de Geologia, Universidad de Chile" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">R</collectionCode>
</emphasis>
vein not forming 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3FFF9F9DF9FEDFFC4E9973" box="[935,956,320,341]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">Rt</emphasis>
(radial triangular). Fore leg walking...................................................................................................................................................................3
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="308F2E675E3FFF9F9EF8FEE7FB3B998D" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E3FFF9F9EF8FEE7FB3A99A8" blockId="6.[166,1225,175,974]" box="[166,1224,376,398]" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
<keyLead id="308A95F75E3FFF9F9EF8FEE7FB3A99A8" box="[166,1224,376,398]" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
4. Fore wing longer than 
<quantity id="4C839B275E3FFF9F9F94FEE7FDFE99A8" box="[458,524,376,398]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="6" pageNumber="107" unit="cm" value="1.2">1.2 cm</quantity>
.............................................................................................................................6
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E3FFF9F9EF8FE0AFB3B998D" blockId="6.[166,1225,175,974]" box="[166,1225,405,427]" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
<keyLead id="308A95F75E3FFF9F9EF8FE0AFB3B998D" box="[166,1225,405,427]" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
— Fore wing shorter than 
<quantity id="4C839B275E3FFF9F9F8CFE0AFDF1998D" box="[466,515,405,427]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="107" unit="cm" value="1.0">1 cm</quantity>
.............................................................................................................................11
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="308F2E675E3FFF9F9EF8FE2DFB3A9A1D" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E3FFF9F9EF8FE2DFB3B99C3" blockId="6.[166,1225,175,974]" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
<keyLead id="308A95F75E3FFF9F9EF8FE2DFB3B99C3" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
5. Wing membrane transparent with many dark spots, main veins brownish. Veins 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3FFF9F9DBAFE2DFC0B99E1" box="[996,1017,434,455]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">Sc</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3FFF9F9A7AFE2CFBC099EE" box="[1060,1074,435,456]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
<collectionCode id="ED6AAE075E3FFF9F9A7AFE2CFBC099EE" box="[1060,1074,435,456]" country="Chile" name="Departamento de Geologia, Universidad de Chile" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">R</collectionCode>
</emphasis>
fused gradually towards wing tip (
<figureCitation id="13402A475E3FFF9F9FC3FE50FE2999C3" box="[413,475,463,485]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[166,199,1704,1726]" captionTargetBox="[361,1040,1032,1662]" captionTargetId="figure-397@6.[342,1049,1004,1703]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 3. Fore wing venation: 3a — Myrmeleontidae (Distoleon Banks, 1810); 3b — Ascalaphidae (Libelloides Schaffer, 1763); 3c — Osmylidae (Osmylus Latreille, 1802); 3d — Chrysopidae (Chrysopa Leach, 1815); 3e — Sisyridae (Sisyra Burmeister, 1839); 3f — Mantispidae (Mantispа Illiger in Kugelann, 1798); 3g — Coniopterigidae (Conwentzia Enderlein 1905); 3h — Hemerobiidae (Hemerobius Linnaeus, 1758); R — radius, Rs — radial sector, Rt — radial triangular, dc — distal cell between R and Rs, Sc — subcostal vein; trz — tiny inserted veins. arranged between the terminal branches of longitudinal veins." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404186" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404186/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">FIg. 3c</figureCitation>
). Head with three simple ocelli.............................................................. 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D415E3FFF9F9A3CFE50FB3B99C3" box="[1122,1225,463,485]" class="Insecta" family="Osmylidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Osmylidae</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E3FFF9F9EF8FE73FB3A9A1D" blockId="6.[166,1225,175,974]" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
<keyLead id="308A95F75E3FFF9F9EF8FE73FB3A9A1D" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
— Wing membrane transparent without spots, main veins greenish (yellowish in dry specimens). Veins 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3FFF9F9A25FE73FB7D9A27" box="[1147,1167,492,513]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">Sc</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3FFF9F9AE4FE73FB3A9A27" box="[1210,1224,492,513]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
<collectionCode id="ED6AAE075E3FFF9F9AE4FE73FB3A9A27" box="[1210,1224,492,513]" country="Chile" name="Departamento de Geologia, Universidad de Chile" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">R</collectionCode>
</emphasis>
fused at the wing tip, or joined by cross veins, if not fused (
<figureCitation id="13402A475E3FFF9F9CA2FD97FCCA9A38" box="[764,824,520,542]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[166,199,1704,1726]" captionTargetBox="[361,1040,1032,1662]" captionTargetId="figure-397@6.[342,1049,1004,1703]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 3. Fore wing venation: 3a — Myrmeleontidae (Distoleon Banks, 1810); 3b — Ascalaphidae (Libelloides Schaffer, 1763); 3c — Osmylidae (Osmylus Latreille, 1802); 3d — Chrysopidae (Chrysopa Leach, 1815); 3e — Sisyridae (Sisyra Burmeister, 1839); 3f — Mantispidae (Mantispа Illiger in Kugelann, 1798); 3g — Coniopterigidae (Conwentzia Enderlein 1905); 3h — Hemerobiidae (Hemerobius Linnaeus, 1758); R — radius, Rs — radial sector, Rt — radial triangular, dc — distal cell between R and Rs, Sc — subcostal vein; trz — tiny inserted veins. arranged between the terminal branches of longitudinal veins." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404186" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404186/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">FIg. 3d</figureCitation>
). Head without simple ocelli. ........................... ............................................................................................................................................................. 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D415E3FFF9F9A04FDBAFB3A9A1D" authorityName="Schneider" authorityYear="1851" box="[1114,1224,549,571]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Chrysopidae</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="308F2E675E3FFF9F9EF8FDDDFB3A9A53" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E3FFF9F9EF8FDDDFB3B9A7E" blockId="6.[166,1225,175,974]" box="[166,1225,578,600]" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
<keyLead id="308A95F75E3FFF9F9EF8FDDDFB3B9A7E" box="[166,1225,578,600]" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
6. Fore wing longer than 
<quantity id="4C839B275E3FFF9F9F94FDDDFDFE9A7E" box="[458,524,578,600]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="107" unit="cm" value="0.6">0.6 cm</quantity>
. .......................................................................................................................... 7
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E3FFF9F9EF8FDC0FB3A9A53" blockId="6.[166,1225,175,974]" box="[166,1224,607,629]" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
<keyLead id="308A95F75E3FFF9F9EF8FDC0FB3A9A53" box="[166,1224,607,629]" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
— Fore wing shorter than 
<quantity id="4C839B275E3FFF9F9F8CFDC0FDE69A53" box="[466,532,607,629]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="107" unit="cm" value="0.5">0.5 cm</quantity>
.........................................................................................................................13
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="308F2E675E3FFF9F9EF8FDE3FB3A9B04" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E3FFF9F9EF8FDE3FB3B9AED" blockId="6.[166,1225,175,974]" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
<keyLead id="308A95F75E3FFF9F9EF8FDE3FB3B9AED" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
7. Wing membrane transparent, often with dark spots or characteristic drawings. Fore wing with two or more branches 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3FFF9F9FDAFD06FE689A88" box="[388,410,665,686]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">Rs</emphasis>
; 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3FFF9F9FFBFD06FE489A88" box="[421,442,665,686]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">Sc</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3FFF9F9FB6FD06FE049A88" box="[488,502,665,686]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
<collectionCode id="ED6AAE075E3FFF9F9FB6FD06FE049A88" box="[488,502,665,686]" country="Chile" name="Departamento de Geologia, Universidad de Chile" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">R</collectionCode>
</emphasis>
terminate separately. Radial sector with many cross veins. Numerous 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3FFF9F9AD3FD06FB559A88" box="[1165,1191,665,686]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">trz</emphasis>
are clearly visible on wing edges (
<figureCitation id="13402A475E3FFF9F9C55FD2AFDBE9AED" box="[523,588,693,715]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[166,199,1704,1726]" captionTargetBox="[361,1040,1032,1662]" captionTargetId="figure-397@6.[342,1049,1004,1703]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 3. Fore wing venation: 3a — Myrmeleontidae (Distoleon Banks, 1810); 3b — Ascalaphidae (Libelloides Schaffer, 1763); 3c — Osmylidae (Osmylus Latreille, 1802); 3d — Chrysopidae (Chrysopa Leach, 1815); 3e — Sisyridae (Sisyra Burmeister, 1839); 3f — Mantispidae (Mantispа Illiger in Kugelann, 1798); 3g — Coniopterigidae (Conwentzia Enderlein 1905); 3h — Hemerobiidae (Hemerobius Linnaeus, 1758); R — radius, Rs — radial sector, Rt — radial triangular, dc — distal cell between R and Rs, Sc — subcostal vein; trz — tiny inserted veins. arranged between the terminal branches of longitudinal veins." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404186" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404186/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">FIg. 3h</figureCitation>
). ........................................................................................ 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D415E3FFF9F9A1EFD2AFB3B9AED" box="[1088,1225,693,715]" class="Insecta" family="Hemerobiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Hemerobiidae</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E3FFF9F9EF8FD4DFB3A9B04" blockId="6.[166,1225,175,974]" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
<keyLead id="308A95F75E3FFF9F9EF8FD4DFB3A9B04" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
— Wing membrane transparent, uniformly brownish colored, lacking spots and pattern. Fore wing with only one branch 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3FFF9F9FC7FD6FFE239B22" box="[409,465,751,773]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">Rs; Sc</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3FFF9F9C5AFD6FFDE09B23" box="[516,530,752,773]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
<collectionCode id="ED6AAE075E3FFF9F9C5AFD6FFDE09B23" box="[516,530,752,773]" country="Chile" name="Departamento de Geologia, Universidad de Chile" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">R</collectionCode>
</emphasis>
are fused near wing tip, vein 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3FFF9F9D64FD70FCBD9B22" box="[826,847,751,772]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">Sc</emphasis>
is steeply curved before fusion with 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3FFF9F9AE4FD6FFB3A9B23" box="[1210,1224,752,773]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
<collectionCode id="ED6AAE075E3FFF9F9AE4FD6FFB3A9B23" box="[1210,1224,752,773]" country="Chile" name="Departamento de Geologia, Universidad de Chile" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">R</collectionCode>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="13402A475E3FFF9F9EA6FC93FEC79B04" box="[248,309,780,802]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[166,199,1704,1726]" captionTargetBox="[361,1040,1032,1662]" captionTargetId="figure-397@6.[342,1049,1004,1703]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 3. Fore wing venation: 3a — Myrmeleontidae (Distoleon Banks, 1810); 3b — Ascalaphidae (Libelloides Schaffer, 1763); 3c — Osmylidae (Osmylus Latreille, 1802); 3d — Chrysopidae (Chrysopa Leach, 1815); 3e — Sisyridae (Sisyra Burmeister, 1839); 3f — Mantispidae (Mantispа Illiger in Kugelann, 1798); 3g — Coniopterigidae (Conwentzia Enderlein 1905); 3h — Hemerobiidae (Hemerobius Linnaeus, 1758); R — radius, Rs — radial sector, Rt — radial triangular, dc — distal cell between R and Rs, Sc — subcostal vein; trz — tiny inserted veins. arranged between the terminal branches of longitudinal veins." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404186" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404186/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">FIg. 3e</figureCitation>
). Radial sector includes few cross veins. Wing edges lacking 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3FFF9F9D29FC93FC659B07" box="[887,919,780,801]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">trz.</emphasis>
..................................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D415E3FFF9F9A2CFC93FB3A9B04" box="[1138,1224,780,802]" class="Insecta" family="Sisyridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Sisyridae</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="308F2E675E3FFF9F9EF8FCB7FB3B9BE8" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E3FFF9F9EF8FCB7FB3A9B5E" blockId="6.[166,1225,175,974]" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
<keyLead id="308A95F75E3FFF9F9EF8FCB7FB3A9B5E" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
6. Body and wings covered with white wax-like coating. Wings lack setae and spots. Venation simple: few cross veins, not more than 5; costal sector lacking cross veins; longitudinal veins without branching (
<figureCitation id="13402A475E3FFF9F9EA6FCFDFEC49B5E" box="[248,310,866,888]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[166,199,1704,1726]" captionTargetBox="[361,1040,1032,1662]" captionTargetId="figure-397@6.[342,1049,1004,1703]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 3. Fore wing venation: 3a — Myrmeleontidae (Distoleon Banks, 1810); 3b — Ascalaphidae (Libelloides Schaffer, 1763); 3c — Osmylidae (Osmylus Latreille, 1802); 3d — Chrysopidae (Chrysopa Leach, 1815); 3e — Sisyridae (Sisyra Burmeister, 1839); 3f — Mantispidae (Mantispа Illiger in Kugelann, 1798); 3g — Coniopterigidae (Conwentzia Enderlein 1905); 3h — Hemerobiidae (Hemerobius Linnaeus, 1758); R — radius, Rs — radial sector, Rt — radial triangular, dc — distal cell between R and Rs, Sc — subcostal vein; trz — tiny inserted veins. arranged between the terminal branches of longitudinal veins." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404186" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404186/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
FIg. 
<quantity id="4C839B275E3FFF9F9F43FCFDFEC49B5E" box="[285,310,866,888]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="3.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="107" unit="g" value="3.0">3g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
). Female ovipositor lacking. ...................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D415E3FFF9F9A79FCFDFB3A9B5E" authorityName="Burmeister" authorityYear="1839" box="[1063,1224,866,888]" class="Insecta" family="Coniopterygidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Coniopterygidae</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E3FFF9F9EF8FCE0FB3B9BE8" blockId="6.[166,1225,175,974]" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
<keyLead id="308A95F75E3FFF9F9EF8FCE0FB3B9BE8" pageId="6" pageNumber="107">
— White wax-like coating lacking. Wings covered with long dense setae, usually with characteristic drawings, including numerous brown spots and stripes. Venation is dense and complex: many cross veins. Female has a long saber-like ovipositor. ................................................................................. 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D415E3FFF9F9A31FC27FB3B9BE8" authorityName="Newman" authorityYear="1853" box="[1135,1225,952,974]" class="Insecta" family="Dilaridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Dilaridae</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
</subSubSection>
</keyStep>
</key>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
